         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25/4/80. ¶  ¶ In casting a glance over your &amp; Mr Benthams admirable volume III, p. I, ¶  dear Sir Joseph, I notice a few omissions, to which you may allow me to draw attention. I had some noted in for...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">80.04.25</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, f. 268.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>MS annotation by Hooker: 'And'; see J. Hooker to M, 10 June 1880.</p>
               </note>25/4/80.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In casting a glance over your &amp; Mr Benthams admirable volume III, p. I,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
               </note> dear Sir Joseph, I notice a few omissions, to which you may allow me to draw attention. I had some noted in former volumes &amp; ventured to submit the memoranda at least in part to you. <name key="Balanops">Balanops</name> occurs at Rockinghams Bay<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Qld.</p>
               </note> &amp; I had placed it also near <name key="Quercus">Quercus</name>, but had no flowers.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M described <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Balanops">Balanops</name> australiana</seg> in B77.10.02, p. 114, noting that male flowers were unknown. <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Balanops">Balanops</name>
                     </seg> is treated on p. 341 of Part I of volume 3 of Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83), where the locality of its six species is given as 'omnes Novo-Caledonicae' [all New Caledonia]. There is an interleaved copy of this part at RBG Kew, with an annotation on the blank page opposite the entry 'Rockingham Bay. Mueller in litt 25/4/80'. There are similar entries incorporating the information in this letter for <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Nuytsia">Nuytsia</name>
                     </seg> (op. p. 206), <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Laurineae">Laurineae</name>
                     </seg> (op. p. 147); <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Batis">Batis</name>
                     </seg> (op. p. 88), which also incorporates information from M. to J. Hooker, 10 August 1880; <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Muehlenbeckia</seg> (p. 102) where (Meissn.) has been struck through and 'F. Muell.' added by J. Hooker in the margin.</p>
               </note> I sent the fruit-specimen to you (now many years ago) &amp; you said, that the same genus occurred in Polynesia, but thought it stood near <name key="Eurya">Eurya</name>.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letters not found.</p>
               </note> — <name key="Nuytsia">Nuytsia</name> has quite the habit of a <name key="Grevillea">Grevillea</name>. The anthers of <name key="Laurineae">Laurineae</name> occur also in <name key="Combretaceae">Combretaceae</name> (Gyrocarpus). — <name key="Batis">Batis</name> seems to me to be a Halorageous plant, as stated by me in print some years ago.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B76.13.03, p. 31.</p>
               </note>
               <name key="Piperaceae">Piperaceae</name> occur for extratropical NZ. &amp; Chath-islands.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This paragraph is marked with a line and an annotation that is partially obscured by binding: '[vix extra tropicos]'. Hooker takes up this point in his reply.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am not aware, that Meissner ever saw <name key="Muehlenbeckia%20platyclada">Muehlenbeckia platyclada</name> (so named by me in the Bot. Mag);<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83), vol. 3, part 1, p. 102 discuss 'M. platyclada Meissn', citing <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Botanical magazine</seg>, vol. 89, 1863, t. 5382, as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Coccoloba platyclada</seg>
                     <seg style="font-weight: bold; ">. </seg>The text accompanying the plate attributes the specimen figured to M as collector, and the name also to M, but in synonomy, from M's earliest description as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Polygonum platycladum </seg>in B57.09.04, p. 73. M discusses the generic relationships in M to W. Hooker, 23 January 1863.</p>
               </note> I corresponded with him to his lamented death. Do you now distinguish only one Telopea? I will send you a specimen of <name key="Eubothrium%20Wickhami">Eubothrium Wickhami</name>. (Hill sent it as a <name key="Stenocarpus">Stenocarpus</name> to me)<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>There are double vertical lines in the central and right margins adjacent to this sentence. M must have misread the text on p. 104 which states 'Species 2. Australiensis' citing Bentham (1863-78), vol. 6, p. 234. Bentham &amp; Hooker go on to compare the genus with <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Embothrio </seg>(<seg style="font-style: italic; ">sic</seg>), and asking whether<seg style="font-style: italic; "> E. Wickhami</seg> F. Muell., which was unknown to them ('nobis ignotam') is intermediate. See B74.04.01, p. 164.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I should have liked the name Saxono-Gothaea used in my report in 1858 &amp;c substituted for Saxe-Gothaea. <name key="Strangea">Strangea</name> seems still to me a good genus.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Saxegothea</seg> is treated on p. 434; <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Strangea">Strangea</name>
                     </seg> is discussed and rejected as a distinct genus on p. 181, referring to M's discussion in B71.07.01, p. 131.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hoping that you deem my frankness not intrusive, &amp; trusting that your great work will come to speedy &amp; glorious conclusion with a full supplement, I remain</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">your regardful</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Do you like Raddlikofers split up genera of <name key="Sapindaceae">Sapindaceae</name>.<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Radlkofer (1875), where the genus is split into many sections; Radlkofer (1879).</p>
               </note> I do not! the splitting process is no gain &amp; only encumbers memory.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
